          "body": "Psalm 96 is one of the Old Testament's most explicitly missionary texts, and it embeds the missionary mandate within the structure of worship itself. Verse 2 commands: 'Proclaim good tidings of His salvation from day to day' — the verb *basar* is the exact Hebrew root behind the Greek *euangelizomai*, to evangelize, to bring good news. Peter Craigie (Psalms 1-50, WBC) notes that the Psalter's enthronement psalms consistently move from sanctuary to nations, from vertical praise to horizontal proclamation. Verses 3, 7, and 10 name three specific missionary acts: *tell* His glory among the nations, *ascribe* to the Lord the glory due His name (calling the families of the peoples to worship), and *say among the nations* 'the Lord reigns.' Worship that never faces outward — toward the nations, toward the unbeliever, toward the proclamation of Yahweh's salvation — has contracted below the psalm's own vision. The nine imperatives of vv. 1-9 are issued to a congregation that is simultaneously a worshiping community and a sent people."
