    "intro": "Interpretation moves from what the text says to what it means — discerning the psalmist's intent within the canonical and historical context of ancient Israel's worship, and tracing the psalm's argument across its three movements. Psalm 96 is not a private devotional poem; it is a liturgical-theological manifesto about the universal kingship of Yahweh, the emptiness of all competing gods, and the eschatological certainty of His just arrival. Where Hebrew vocabulary sharpens the English, a brief note supplements the interpretation.",
