        "excerpt": "Sing to the Lord a new song; Sing to the Lord, all the earth.",
        "body": "The psalm opens with an avalanche of imperatives. Before the psalmist has offered a single reason for worship, he has issued three commands to sing (vv. 1-2), two to proclaim (vv. 2-3), and one to tell (v. 3). The rhetorical effect is deliberate: the imperatives arrive with the force of a summons before the doctrinal grounds are given, exactly as a royal herald announces the king's presence before explaining his credentials. The audience is not Israel alone but 'all the earth' (*kol-erets*, v. 1) — a universalism that places Psalm 96 in the company of Abraham's promise that 'all the families of the earth shall be blessed' (Genesis 12:3) and Isaiah's vision of the nations streaming to Zion (Isaiah 2:2-4).\n\nThe grounds arrive in verses 4-6. The *for* (*ki*) of verse 4 introduces the doctrinal engine: Yahweh is great, greatly to be praised, and to be feared above all gods. Verse 5 presses the comparison to its terminus: all the gods of the peoples are *elilim* — nothings — while Yahweh made the heavens. The contrast is not between more powerful and less powerful beings; it is between the Creator and non-entities. The creator-creature distinction is the decisive polemic. No idol made what Yahweh made; therefore no idol commands the worship that Yahweh commands.\n\nVerse 6 pictures the court of Yahweh. Splendor (*hod*) and majesty (*hadar*) are before Him — the vocabulary of royal court attendants, now personified as qualities that surround His presence. Strength (*oz*) and beauty (*tipharah*) fill His sanctuary. The sanctuary here is the Jerusalem temple, but the psalmist is making a claim about what the sanctuary *contains* — not liturgical furniture but the moral and aesthetic qualities of Yahweh's own character, manifested in the space He inhabits. Derek Kidner notes that the pairing of strength and beauty (*oz* and *tipharah*) describes a God who is neither merely powerful nor merely aesthetic, but who holds both in perfect integration — the kind of beauty that does not compromise strength and the kind of strength that does not forfeit beauty.\n\nThe nine imperatives of vv. 1-9 together constitute what Walter Brueggemann (The Psalms and the Life of Faith) calls a 'counter-liturgy' — a worship-script designed to re-form the imagination of the worshiper against the competing worship-scripts of the surrounding nations. Every time the congregation sang Psalm 96, they were rehearsing a world in which Yahweh is king, the idols are nothing, and the proper response to that reality is song, proclamation, and trembling adoration.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shir chadash* (new song) — *chadash* means renewed, fresh, qualitatively new-for-the-occasion. *Elilim* (nothings) — from *elil*, worthless, futile; a deliberate paronomasia on *elohim* (gods). *Hod* (splendor) and *hadar* (majesty) are paired frequently in royal psalms (Psalm 21:5; 45:3-4; 104:1) — they are the vocabulary of divine and royal magnificence."
