        "body": "The psalm's second movement turns outward with renewed intensity. The three-repeated *yahav* ('ascribe,' vv. 7-8) calls the *mishpachot amim* — the families of the peoples, Gentile clans and kindreds — to render to Yahweh what is already His. The verb *yahav* carries the sense of giving what is owed, not giving what you choose to donate. Glory and strength belong to Yahweh by right; the nations are called to *recognize* and *render* what He already possesses. This is not flattery but reattribution — the restoration of proper cosmic order.\n\nVerse 8 adds a cultic dimension: bring an offering (*minchah*) and come into His courts. The *minchah* in the Pentateuch is the grain offering (Leviticus 2) — a material, tangible act of consecration. The psalmist envisions the nations not merely acknowledging Yahweh from a distance but entering the sanctuary courts with physical offerings. This is the eschatological pilgrimage of Isaiah 60:3-7 and Zechariah 14:16-17 anticipated in liturgical form. Worship has a body; it costs something.\n\nVerse 9 holds the twin postures of worship: holy attire and trembling. The phrase *hadarah qodesh* ('in holy attire' or 'in the beauty of holiness') has been interpreted two ways by orthodox commentators. The Reformers generally read it as an adverbial phrase about the worshiper's spiritual condition — 'in holy array,' wearing holiness as a garment. The cultic reading sees literal priestly vestments or festal dress. Both readings agree on the underlying principle: the approach to Yahweh requires that the worshiper be *dressed for the occasion*, that worship is not casual or careless. The companion command — 'tremble before Him, all the earth' — introduces physical-existential awe, the body's honest reckoning with the reality of holiness.\n\nVerse 10 is the psalm's theological center of gravity: 'The Lord reigns.' These three Hebrew words (*yehovah malakh*) are the enthronement shout — the liturgical proclamation that sets the entire Psalms 93-99 cluster in motion. The claim is tripartite: Yahweh reigns (present reality), the world is firmly established under His governance and cannot be moved (creation's stability as a function of divine rule), and He will judge the peoples with equity (*meshar*, uprightness, evenness — the standard of a just scale). The congregation is then commanded to *say* this among the nations — to take the enthronement proclamation outside the sanctuary and into the streets of Gentile cities. Missionary proclamation is an act of worship performed in enemy territory.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishpachot amim* (families of the peoples) — the kinship-group word *mishpachah* is used, emphasizing that the call extends to every clan-level social unit among the nations. *Minchah* (offering) — the grain/tribute offering; also used of gifts brought to a superior, emphasizing Yahweh's royal status. *Malakh* (reigns) — the Hebrew perfect used as a proclamation ('Yahweh has become king, Yahweh is king'); *meshar* (equity) — from the root meaning straight, level, upright — the imagery of a fair measuring rod."
