        "body": "The psalm's final movement performs a remarkable reversal. For nine verses, human worshipers have been commanded to praise. Now the direction of command shifts — the psalmist calls on the non-human creation itself to join the chorus. Heavens (*shamayim*), earth (*erets*), sea (*yam*), fields (*saday*), and forests (*yaar*) are each summoned with their own verb: *samach* (be glad), *gil* (rejoice), *raam* (roar/resound), *alaz* (exult), *run* (sing for joy). These are not metaphors for human emotions projected onto nature; they are a genuine expansion of the worshiping community to include every domain of the created order. The Old Testament's cosmic praise tradition (Psalm 19:1-6; 148; Isaiah 55:12; Job 38:7) understands creation as having genuine doxological capacity — it was made to declare and reflect the glory of its Maker.\n\nThe ground for creation's joy is given in verse 13: 'for He is coming, for He is coming to judge the earth.' The double *ki-ba* ('for He is coming') is the Hebrew repetition of certainty and emphasis — not 'perhaps He will come' but 'He is indeed coming, He is certainly coming.' The judgment announced here is not cause for terror in the psalm's framework but cause for gladness. This is the psalm's most theologically acute move. A world groaning under injustice, in which the wicked prosper and the righteous suffer (Psalm 73), welcomes a judge who will judge in *tsedeq* (righteousness) and *emunah* (faithfulness). The ground shifts from 'coming' to the character of the one who comes: He judges in righteousness (His verdicts conform to His own character, not to power or bribery) and in faithfulness (He keeps every promise He has made — to vindicate the righteous, to expose the wicked, to make all things right).\n\nPaul hears this psalm in Romans 8:19-22, where creation 'eagerly awaits' the revelation of the sons of God and groans in anticipation of liberation from its bondage to decay. The creation that groans and the creation that sings are the same creation — singing because the groaning will end, because the judge who comes is qualified by righteousness and faithfulness to bring it to its proper end. Tim Keller (The Songs of Jesus, 2015) observes that only a just judge can produce genuine gladness in all parties — any other judge produces winners and losers, but the righteous judge produces the vindication of the whole created order.\n\nThe psalm ends without a closing doxology or benediction — it simply stops at the announcement of His coming. This is itself a rhetorical device: the reader is left standing in the psalm's eschatological horizon, between the present imperatives of worship and the future certainty of His arrival. The new song of verse 1 has found its final note: the universe is tuning itself for the arrival of its rightful King.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Samach* (be glad), *gil* (rejoice, spin with joy), *raam* (thunder, roar), *alaz* (exult), *run* (cry out for joy, shout) — five different verbs for five domains of creation, each with its own mode of praise. *Tsedeq* (righteousness) and *emunah* (faithfulness) — the pairing occurs at Psalm 89:14 and Isaiah 11:5 in royal/messianic contexts; the coming judge is recognizably the Davidic king of Psalm 72 who 'judges the people in righteousness' (72:2)."
