        "body": "Psalm 96's enthronement proclamation — 'the Lord reigns' (96:10) — stands at the center of the Old Testament's royal theology, and that theology finds its fulfillment in Jesus Christ. The New Testament's appropriation of the psalm is substantial. The double 'for He is coming' (96:13) is the OT's most direct antecedent to the NT's *parousia* language — the same vocabulary of royal arrival that Paul uses in 1 Thessalonians 4:15-17 and 1 Corinthians 15:23, and that Revelation deploys with the refrain 'Behold, He is coming' (Revelation 1:7; 22:12, 20). The judge who will judge the world in righteousness and faithfulness is identified by the New Testament as the resurrected Christ: 'He has fixed a day on which He will judge the world in righteousness by a Man whom He has appointed' (Acts 17:31). The Son of Man who comes in Matthew 25:31-46 to judge the nations is the psalm's arriving king given flesh and name.\n\nThe missionary structure of the psalm likewise anticipates the Great Commission. The command to 'say among the nations, the Lord reigns' (96:10) becomes, through the resurrection, the commission to 'make disciples of all nations' (Matthew 28:19). The *basar* (proclaim good tidings) of verse 2 becomes the *euangelion* — the gospel. The nations who are commanded to bring offerings into Yahweh's courts (96:8) find their eschatological fulfillment in Revelation 21:24-26, where the kings of the earth bring their glory into the New Jerusalem.\n\nThe Reformed tradition has read this psalm as the church's missionary mandate rooted in the present reign of Christ (John Calvin, Commentary on the Psalms: 'The prophet calls the whole world to celebrate the praises of God, because God willed that His name should be known through the whole world, and His salvation declared to all nations'). The New Song of v. 1 is, in the New Testament's reading, the song of the redeemed from every tribe and tongue and people and nation (Revelation 5:9) — the *shir chadash* that cannot be contained within the boundaries of Israel because the One it celebrates cannot be contained within those boundaries.\n\nThe psalm is, therefore, not merely ancient Israelite liturgy. It is the world's worship score — composed before the Messiah arrived, waiting for the choir that His arrival would assemble, reaching its final note only when He comes to judge the earth in the righteousness and faithfulness the psalm promises. Every time the church sings Psalm 96, it is rehearsing both its present commission (proclaim among the nations) and its eschatological confidence (He is coming, He is coming)."
